const section=(id:string,title:string,paragraphs:string[],relatedBranchIds?:string[],relatedPhilosopherIds?:string[],relatedWorkTitles?:string[]):ArticleSection=>({id,title,paragraphs,relatedBranchIds,relatedPhilosopherIds,relatedWorkTitles});

export const hellenisticPhilosopherArticles:Record<string,ArticleSection[]>={
  epicurus:[
    section('overview','Philosophy as freedom from needless fear',[
      'Epicurus built a complete philosophical system around a practical question: what prevents human beings from living pleasantly and securely? His answer is not that people lack luxury. They are disturbed by false beliefs about what they need, by unlimited competition for status, by fear of divine punishment, and by terror at the thought of death. Philosophy works as therapy because arguments about nature, knowledge, and desire can remove these sources of disturbance. Pleasure names the healthy condition that becomes available when bodily pain and mental turmoil no longer govern a life.',
      'This project joins physics, epistemology, ethics, and community. Atomism explains events without appealing to divine anger or cosmic purpose. An account of perception supplies confidence that inquiry can begin from experience. A disciplined classification of desires separates genuine needs from socially manufactured cravings. Friendship and the Garden create conditions in which people can practice security together. Epicurus therefore cannot be reduced to a recommendation to enjoy oneself. He asks which pleasures make future disturbance less likely, which desires can actually be completed, and which beliefs keep fear alive.'
    ],['epicureanism','ethics','metaphysics'],['democritus','lucretius'],['Letter to Menoeceus','Principal Doctrines']),
    section('hellenistic-world','The Hellenistic world after Alexander',[
      'Epicurus was born in 341 BCE, when the political world organized around the independent Greek polis was being transformed by Macedonian power and the conquests of Alexander. His adult life unfolded amid successor kingdoms, military conflict, migration, and unstable relations between cities and rulers. Philosophy did not suddenly abandon politics, but schools increasingly asked how a person might achieve freedom and steadiness when public circumstances exceeded individual control. Epicureanism, Stoicism, Cynicism, and Skepticism offered sharply different answers to that shared pressure.',
      'Epicurus studied and taught in several cities before purchasing a property in Athens around 306 BCE. His school entered a landscape already marked by Plato’s Academy and Aristotle’s Lyceum, yet it challenged their models of intellectual and social authority. Epicurus rejected the search for transcendent Forms and the explanation of nature through intrinsic purposes. He also distrusted the pursuit of political honor as a route to security. The problem was not merely that public life could be dangerous. Ambition trains desire on goods that depend on unstable opinion, making tranquility hostage to other people’s approval.'
    ],['ancient-greek','epicureanism','stoicism'],['plato','aristotle','zeno'],[]),
    section('garden','The Garden as a philosophical community',[
      'The Garden was both a place and a social experiment. Epicurean philosophy was learned through shared meals, correspondence, memorized summaries, frank correction, and durable friendship. Ancient reports emphasize that women and enslaved people participated in the community, an unusual feature among major Athenian schools even though the surviving evidence does not let us reconstruct equality in modern terms. The Garden offered an alternative measure of success: not rank in the city, but the capacity to live without domination by fear, vanity, or unlimited need.',
      'Withdrawal from corrosive ambition did not mean solitary selfishness. Epicurus treats friendship as one of the greatest means to security, and Epicurean communities maintained connections across cities and generations. Friends provide practical help, but the value of friendship exceeds calculation because trust changes how the future is experienced. A person surrounded by reliable companions does not face every threat as an isolated competitor. The Garden therefore turns ethics into a shared environment. Simplicity becomes easier when a community does not reward display, and philosophical correction becomes bearable when it occurs among people committed to one another’s freedom.'
    ],['epicureanism','ethics'],['epicurus','lucretius'],['Vatican Sayings']),
    section('pleasure','Pleasure without the banquet caricature',[
      'Epicurus identifies pleasure as the good, but his hedonism is disciplined by an analysis of consequence. A pleasant experience can be rejected when it produces greater pain, and a painful effort can be chosen when it secures a more stable pleasure. The measure is not the intensity of the present sensation alone. It is the condition of a whole life as desire, memory, expectation, body, and friendship interact. Practical wisdom is therefore indispensable: it calculates which choices reduce dependency and which apparently attractive pleasures train new forms of anxiety.',
      'The most important pleasures are often described negatively: aponia, absence of bodily pain, and ataraxia, freedom from mental disturbance. Negative does not mean empty or numb. When thirst is removed, the resulting ease is already pleasurable; no escalating stimulation is required to make the condition complete. Epicurus distinguishes this stable pleasure from pleasures of active variation. The distinction explains why simple food can rival luxury when hunger is satisfied. Luxury is not forbidden, but dependence on it makes fortune the manager of one’s well-being. Epicurean pleasure is radical because it claims enough can be recognized and reached.'
    ],['epicureanism','ethics'],['epicurus','aristotle'],['Letter to Menoeceus']),
    section('desires','Natural, necessary, and empty desires',[
      'Epicurus classifies desires to make them governable. Some are natural and necessary, including needs connected to survival, bodily ease, and happiness. Some are natural but unnecessary, such as preferences for more elaborate versions of satisfactions that could be achieved simply. Others are empty or groundless, especially desires for unlimited wealth, fame, power, or immortality. These categories are diagnostic rather than puritanical. The question is whether a desire has a natural point of completion and whether satisfying it produces security or merely renews the race.',
      'An empty desire is difficult to complete because its standard comes from comparison and imagination. There is no natural amount of fame that guarantees freedom from fear, and political power creates new threats as quickly as it removes old ones. By contrast, understanding the limits of bodily need makes abundance available even under modest conditions. This argument challenges societies that organize aspiration around permanent dissatisfaction. Epicurus does not deny that deprivation and violence cause real pain. He instead distinguishes those harms from anxieties multiplied by false belief, allowing philosophy to reduce suffering without pretending it can abolish every external danger.'
    ],['epicureanism','ethics','political-philosophy'],['epicurus'],['Principal Doctrines','Vatican Sayings']),
    section('physics','Atoms, void, and natural explanation',[
      'Epicurus adapts the atomism associated with Leucippus and Democritus. Bodies are composed of indivisible atoms moving through void; compounds form and dissolve, while the basic constituents do not come from nothing or vanish into nothing. This physics removes the need to explain storms, eclipses, disease, or death as interventions by offended gods. Natural inquiry matters ethically because a person who treats unusual events as divine warnings remains vulnerable to interpreters who claim authority over hidden powers. Understanding possible natural causes loosens that dependence.',
      'Epicurean physics does not demand one dogmatic explanation where evidence permits several. For distant celestial events, multiple natural accounts may be compatible with appearances, and the therapeutic aim is achieved when supernatural terror is excluded. The controversial atomic swerve, especially prominent in Lucretius, introduces a minimal deviation from strictly parallel downward motion. Interpreters debate its relation to agency and free action. Whatever role it plays, Epicurus’ larger project resists both providential teleology and fatalistic resignation: human choices occur within nature, and understanding nature can alter the beliefs through which people act.'
    ],['epicureanism','metaphysics','philosophy-of-science'],['democritus','lucretius'],['On the Nature of Things']),
    section('knowledge','Sensation, preconceptions, and feelings',[
      'Epicurean epistemology begins from criteria through which inquiry becomes possible: sensations, preconceptions, and feelings of pleasure and pain. Sensations are not themselves false in the way judgments can be false. They register an appearance produced through interaction with the world; error enters when a person adds an interpretation that the evidence does not support. A distant tower may appear round and later square, but the conflict belongs to hasty judgment if one concludes that the first appearance guaranteed the tower’s shape at close range.',
      'Preconceptions are general recognitions formed through repeated experience, enabling people to understand and investigate terms such as human being or justice. Feelings register pleasure and pain and therefore orient choice and avoidance. These criteria do not make every opinion true. Epicureans insist that judgments must await confirmation or avoid contradiction by further experience. The account supports materialist inquiry without demanding impossible certainty. It also connects knowledge to therapy: fears about gods or death are not defeated by reassurance alone, but by testing the judgments that extend beyond what sensation and sound inference warrant.'
    ],['epicureanism','epistemology','skepticism'],['epicurus'],['Principal Doctrines']),
    section('gods-death','Gods, death, and the removal of terror',[
      'Epicurus does not simply announce that gods do not exist. Surviving texts describe blessed and imperishable gods, but deny that such beings manage weather, reward cities, punish wrongdoing, or arrange the cosmos for human purposes. A blessed being would not be burdened by anger and administration. Popular religion insults divine perfection when it imagines gods as anxious rulers. Whether the Epicurean gods are understood as real beings, ideal constructions, or objects of a distinctive kind of thought, their ethical role is clear: divine life should model tranquility rather than authorize fear.',
      'The argument about death is similarly exact. Death is nothing to us because all good and bad experience depends on sensation, and death is the absence of sensation. While we exist, death is not present; when death is present, we no longer exist to suffer it. This does not deny grief, the pain of dying, or concern about how one’s life affects friends. It targets the imagined experience of being dead and deprived forever. Removing that fantasy changes present life: mortality no longer makes unlimited time a condition of happiness, and fear no longer grants priests or rulers an easy instrument of control.'
    ],['epicureanism','philosophy-of-religion','ethics'],['epicurus','lucretius'],['Letter to Menoeceus','On the Nature of Things']),
    section('surviving-works','Letters, doctrines, sayings, and Lucretius',[
      'Most of Epicurus’ extensive writings are lost. The surviving core includes three letters preserved by Diogenes Laertius, the Principal Doctrines, the Vatican Sayings, fragments, and papyri from Herculaneum associated with later Epicureans. The Letter to Menoeceus compresses the ethical therapy around gods, death, desire, pleasure, and practical wisdom. The Letter to Herodotus summarizes physics, while the Letter to Pythocles addresses celestial phenomena. These summaries were designed for recollection: students could keep the system available when fear or desire distorted judgment.',
      'The Principal Doctrines and Vatican Sayings present compact claims that require interpretation within the larger system. Their brevity can invite slogan reading, yet they functioned as prompts for practice and discussion. Lucretius’ Latin poem De Rerum Natura, written centuries later, is the fullest surviving literary presentation of Epicurean physics and therapy. Its explanations of atoms, mortality, desire, love, plague, and civilization show how poetry can make difficult natural philosophy emotionally persuasive. Lucretius does not merely preserve Epicurus; he stages the struggle required for an argument to reach a fearful imagination. The poetic address also shows that knowing a doctrine abstractly may not be enough to loosen habits formed by religious dread or social competition.'
    ],['epicureanism','ancient-greek'],['epicurus','lucretius'],['Letter to Menoeceus','Letter to Herodotus','Principal Doctrines','Vatican Sayings','On the Nature of Things']),
    section('rivals','Rival paths to a good life',[
      'Epicureanism and Stoicism agree that philosophy should transform desire and fear, but disagree about nature, value, and public duty. Stoics identify virtue as the only good and understand the cosmos as providentially ordered; Epicureans identify pleasure as the good and explain nature through non-providential atoms and void. Stoics can treat political and social roles as expressions of rational duty. Epicureans are more suspicious of ambition and ask whether participation produces security or dependence. Neither contrast reduces to toughness versus comfort: both demand disciplined judgment under different accounts of what the world is.',
      'Against Platonism, Epicurus rejects transcendent Forms and an immortal soul. Against Aristotelian teleology, he denies that natural processes must be explained through purposes built into the cosmos. Against Skepticism, Epicureans defend criteria of truth robust enough for confident natural inquiry and therapeutic conclusions. Yet Epicurean caution about unsupported judgment can resemble skeptical restraint. These contrasts reveal why the physics is not optional background. A providential universe, a purposive nature, an unknowable world, and an atomic world generate different fears and different accounts of freedom.'
    ],['epicureanism','stoicism','platonism','aristotelianism','skepticism'],['epicurus','zeno','plato','aristotle'],[]),
    section('legacy-reading','Caricature, revival, and how to read Epicurus',[
      'Epicureanism acquired a reputation for indulgence, atheism, and selfish retreat partly because rivals defined it through polemic. Christian writers often opposed its material mortal soul and denial of providential government, although some could appreciate its criticism of luxury. The rediscovery of Lucretius in the early modern period contributed to renewed interest in atomism and natural explanation. Later thinkers adapted Epicurean themes without accepting the whole system. Modern revivals often value simple pleasure and freedom from fear, but can lose the communal discipline and demanding physics that make those recommendations coherent.',
      'Begin with the Letter to Menoeceus, then read the Principal Doctrines and Vatican Sayings slowly enough to ask what fear or desire each claim addresses. Add the Letter to Herodotus before reading substantial selections from Lucretius, especially the arguments about death and the natural world. Keep three cautions in view. Pleasure is not constant stimulation; withdrawal is not isolation from friends; and natural explanation is not a detached scientific hobby. Epicurus’ central experiment is to see whether a person can become rich by understanding limits rather than by making possession, reputation, or endless life finally sufficient.'
    ],['epicureanism','ethics','philosophy-of-science'],['epicurus','lucretius'],['Letter to Menoeceus','Principal Doctrines','Vatican Sayings','On the Nature of Things'])
  ],
  epictetus:[
    section('overview','Freedom located in judgment and choice',[
      'Epictetus teaches a severe but enabling form of freedom. Bodies can be injured, property taken, offices denied, reputations ruined, and lives ended by powers outside an individual’s command. Yet these events do not by themselves determine the use a person makes of impressions, desires, aversions, and choices. Stoic education therefore concentrates on prohairesis, the rational faculty of choice or moral purpose. Freedom is not exemption from circumstance. It is the trained capacity to withhold assent from false judgments and to act well within the situation one actually occupies.',
      'This teaching is often compressed into a distinction between what is and is not under our control. The compression is useful but risky. Epictetus is not promising emotional invulnerability through positive thinking, and he is not telling people to ignore injustice. He asks agents to locate responsibility accurately so that action is not corrupted by demands for guaranteed outcomes. The distinction belongs to a larger Stoic system of impressions, assent, desire, nature, duty, and social role. Its purpose is disciplined participation, not passive retreat.'
    ],['stoicism','ethics'],['epictetus','zeno','chrysippus'],['Discourses','Enchiridion']),
    section('slavery-context','Slavery, emancipation, and Roman imperial power',[
      'Epictetus was born around 50 CE, probably at Hierapolis in Phrygia, and spent part of his life enslaved in the household of Epaphroditus, a powerful freedman connected to the emperor Nero. He later became free and studied with the Stoic teacher Musonius Rufus. The evidence does not permit a complete biography or a simple explanation of how enslavement shaped every doctrine. It does make his vocabulary of mastery, dependence, compulsion, and freedom impossible to treat as merely decorative. External domination was a lived institution, not an abstract thought experiment.',
      'After the emperor Domitian expelled philosophers from Rome, Epictetus taught at Nicopolis in northwestern Greece. His students included socially privileged young men preparing for public careers. He repeatedly attacks their confidence that status, education, or proximity to power makes them free. A person who must flatter an official to obtain office is dependent even if legally free; a person who treats death as the worst evil can be coerced by anyone able to threaten it. This analysis relocates freedom without denying political power. It shows how external domination gains leverage through judgments about what must be secured at any cost.'
    ],['stoicism','political-philosophy'],['epictetus','seneca'],['Discourses']),
    section('teacher-arrian','A teacher preserved by Arrian',[
      'Epictetus wrote no surviving systematic treatise. What readers possess are works associated with his student Arrian: four surviving books of Discourses, from an original larger set, and the short Enchiridion or Handbook. Arrian presents the Discourses as records of Epictetus’ teaching, but their exact relation to classroom speech remains debated. The voice is confrontational, repetitive, humorous, and responsive to particular students. Epictetus does not simply state Stoic doctrine. He diagnoses vanity, panic, evasion, and inconsistency as they appear in people who know philosophical vocabulary but have not transformed their judgments.',
      'The Enchiridion extracts compact practical reminders from this teaching. Its portability made it influential, but isolation from the Discourses can make it seem like a collection of commands to endure whatever happens. The longer conversations supply arguments, social contexts, and accounts of training. They reveal a teacher who distinguishes stages of education and insists that reading books is not the same as digesting them. Philosophy succeeds when conduct under pressure reflects the principles a student can recite. The preserved form therefore matters: Epictetus reaches readers as an ongoing act of correction rather than a polished system announced from above. His abrupt questions and imagined replies make the reader occupy the uncomfortable position of the student whose excuses have just become visible.'
    ],['stoicism','ancient-greek'],['epictetus'],['Discourses','Enchiridion']),
    section('up-to-us','What is up to us and what is not',[
      'The Enchiridion begins by distinguishing things that are up to us from things that are not. Judgment, impulse, desire, aversion, and whatever counts as our own activity belong on one side; body, property, reputation, office, and whatever is not our own activity belong on the other. The Greek phrase often translated as “in our control” concerns what depends on us or is attributable to our agency. It does not imply effortless command over every thought or feeling. Training is necessary precisely because habits and impressions make good use of agency difficult.',
      'The distinction changes practical reasoning. A speaker can prepare carefully and aim to communicate truthfully, but cannot guarantee applause. A citizen can oppose a policy, but cannot make victory the condition of acting justly. Health deserves appropriate care, yet no amount of care guarantees immunity from illness. Epictetus calls externals indifferent with respect to moral goodness, not irrelevant to choice. The agent should select and use them appropriately while refusing to treat possession of them as the measure of worth. This preserves effort while removing the fantasy that responsible action must control the world.'
    ],['stoicism','ethics'],['epictetus','chrysippus'],['Enchiridion','Discourses']),
    section('prohairesis','Prohairesis and the location of character',[
      'Prohairesis is central to Epictetus’ distinctive presentation of Stoicism. It is variously translated as choice, moral purpose, volition, or faculty of choice, and no single English term captures all its work. It names the capacity through which a person evaluates impressions, forms intentions, and becomes responsible for a way of using circumstances. External events supply material; prohairesis makes that material into action marked by justice or injustice, courage or cowardice, clarity or confusion. Character is therefore not a possession hidden inside the self but a pattern of active use.',
      'Epictetus sometimes speaks as though prohairesis cannot be constrained or harmed by another. That claim does not erase torture, enslavement, deprivation, or psychological injury. It expresses a normative argument about where moral good and evil are located. Another person can block an action’s external completion, but cannot turn a just intention into an unjust one without the agent’s assent. Critics can reasonably ask whether this makes agency too independent of trauma and social formation. The teaching remains powerful when read as a discipline for refusing complicity, not as a denial that oppressive conditions damage lives.'
    ],['stoicism','ethics','political-philosophy'],['epictetus'],['Discourses']),
    section('impressions-assent','Impressions, assent, desire, and aversion',[
      'Stoic psychology treats impressions as appearances or presentations that arise without first asking permission. A sudden noise, insult, illness, or prospect of advancement presents itself together with an apparent significance: danger, humiliation, catastrophe, or opportunity. The first appearance is not yet a fully endorsed judgment. Assent is the act by which the rational agent accepts an impression as true or fitting. Epictetus’ exercises create a pause in which the student can say, in effect, that an appearance is an appearance and must be tested before it governs action.',
      'Desire and aversion follow judgments about good and evil. If office is judged good in itself, desire becomes dependent on patrons and rivals; if death is judged evil in itself, aversion makes every threat overwhelming. Early training may suspend strong desire for externals and direct aversion only toward failures of one’s own agency. This is not a permanent refusal to pursue anything. It is rehabilitation of wanting so that impulse can be guided by appropriate action rather than desperation. Emotional discipline therefore operates through examination of value judgments, not through an order to stop feeling.'
    ],['stoicism','epistemology','ethics'],['epictetus','chrysippus'],['Discourses','Enchiridion']),
    section('nature-roles','Nature, roles, and duties to others',[
      'Epictetus belongs to a Stoic tradition that understands human beings as rational and social parts of nature. Living according to nature is not following spontaneous appetite. It means developing the capacities for reason, cooperation, and appropriate action that characterize a human life within a larger whole. The student must ask not only what is personally bearable but what conduct fits relations such as parent, child, sibling, neighbor, citizen, or friend. These roles generate claims that cannot be reduced to private tranquility.',
      'Role ethics prevents the control distinction from becoming an excuse for withdrawal. A brother’s behavior is not up to the agent, but acting well as a sibling remains the agent’s task. Public success is uncertain, but justice in public conduct remains attributable to choice. Epictetus can also accept inherited social roles too readily, and modern readers should not turn his framework into automatic obedience. Its strongest insight is that freedom and obligation are connected: because outcomes are not ours to guarantee, the ethical question becomes how to perform a role without surrendering judgment to fear, anger, or reward.'
    ],['stoicism','ethics','political-philosophy'],['epictetus','marcus-aurelius'],['Discourses','Enchiridion']),
    section('earlier-stoics','From Zeno and Chrysippus to a Roman classroom',[
      'Epictetus inherits a system developed by Zeno, Cleanthes, Chrysippus, and later Stoics. Early Stoicism joined logic, physics, and ethics. Its account of assent depends on logic and epistemology; its ideal of living according to nature depends on a providential, causally ordered cosmos; its ethics identifies virtue as the only good. Epictetus rarely offers the full technical architecture in classroom discussions, but he presupposes it. His concentration on moral practice is a way of applying the system to students whose problem is not lack of terminology but failure to use it.',
      'Comparison with Seneca and Marcus Aurelius clarifies the Roman development. Seneca writes essays and letters while negotiating wealth, politics, anger, grief, and moral progress. Marcus records private reminders while exercising imperial power. Epictetus speaks as a teacher to students and repeatedly returns them to agency, role, and exercise. Marcus read Epictetus through Arrian and echoes his focus on judgment and social duty. These thinkers are not interchangeable sources of inspirational sayings. Their different genres and positions reveal how Stoic principles change when addressed from a classroom, a court, or an emperor’s private notebook.'
    ],['stoicism','logic','ethics'],['zeno','cleanthes','chrysippus','seneca','marcus-aurelius'],['Discourses','Moral Letters','Meditations']),
    section('exercises','Exercises, progress, and philosophical training',[
      'Epictetus organizes training around disciplines of desire, action, and assent. The discipline of desire aims to prevent frustrated craving and terrified avoidance by aligning value with what depends on agency. The discipline of action concerns appropriate conduct in relationships and roles. The discipline of assent tests impressions so that the mind does not accept contradiction, exaggeration, or seductive appearance. These disciplines overlap, and Epictetus adjusts emphasis to the learner. A beginner who wants to display clever logic may need first to examine why praise has become necessary.',
      'Practical exercises include anticipating difficulties, observing language that treats externals as good or evil, delaying reaction, remembering mortality, and treating daily situations as material for practice. The point is not to perform hardship for its own sake or win a contest in toughness. Training reveals dependency and prepares judgment for pressure. Progress is measured by reduced blame, less theatrical complaint, more reliable social conduct, and willingness to examine one’s own contribution to disturbance. The standard remains demanding, but Epictetus distinguishes a learner making progress from the ideal sage rather than requiring instant perfection.'
    ],['stoicism','ethics'],['epictetus'],['Discourses','Enchiridion']),
    section('passivity','Why the teaching is not passivity',[
      'The most persistent misunderstanding treats Epictetus as teaching resignation: because outcomes are not up to us, nothing should be changed. His actual distinction separates the moral quality of action from guaranteed success. It can support courageous resistance because failure, punishment, and reputation no longer decide whether resistance is worth attempting. Epictetus praises figures who speak frankly under threat and uses Socrates as a model of public integrity. The agent remains responsible for deliberation, effort, and role-based duty even when political power controls the external result.',
      'The danger of passive appropriation is nevertheless real. Advice addressed to a privileged student anxious about reputation can become cruel when imposed on someone facing preventable harm. Stoic distinctions should not be used by institutions to excuse injustice or demand endurance from others. Epictetus’ method is first-personal: examine what your own judgment and action require. Applied responsibly, it does not say suffering is unreal. It asks how fear of suffering can corrupt action and how a person can preserve responsibility without pretending that virtue grants control over material and political conditions.'
    ],['stoicism','political-philosophy','ethics'],['epictetus','socrates'],['Discourses']),
    section('legacy-reading','Influence, modern reception, and how to read Epictetus',[
      'Epictetus influenced Marcus Aurelius and later traditions of moral discipline. Christian readers found affinities in his concern with inner freedom, providence, self-examination, and detachment, while rejecting or transforming Stoic theology and self-sufficiency. Modern psychotherapies, especially cognitive approaches, are often compared with Stoic analysis of judgment and emotion. The relationship is historically meaningful but should not collapse either tradition into the other. Contemporary popular Stoicism has made Epictetus widely accessible, yet it can turn a demanding social ethics into personal optimization or emotional armor.',
      'Begin with selected Discourses before using the Enchiridion as a handbook. Read conversations about impressions, roles, illness, exile, and freedom to see how principles answer particular failures of judgment. Then compare the compact handbook passages with their fuller contexts and with Marcus Aurelius’ private exercises. Keep the technical terms visible: “control” is not omnipotence, “indifferent” is not unimportant, and freedom is not simply feeling calm. Epictetus asks whether a person can make choices answerable to reason and social duty when fear, reward, and power invite surrender.'
    ],['stoicism','ethics'],['epictetus','marcus-aurelius','seneca'],['Discourses','Enchiridion','Meditations'])
  ]
};

export const hellenisticBranchArticles:Record<string,ArticleSection[]>={
  stoicism:[
    section('overview','A system for living as a rational and social being',[
      'Stoicism is a Hellenistic philosophical school that joins an exacting ethics to accounts of logic, knowledge, nature, causation, psychology, and society. Its practical promise is not that disciplined people can make events obey them. It is that they can learn to judge and act well within a world whose outcomes are never entirely theirs. Virtue is the only unconditional good because character determines the quality of every use made of health, wealth, power, pain, pleasure, reputation, and loss. External advantages matter, but none guarantees a good life.',
      'The modern image of Stoicism as calm endurance captures only part of this project. Early Stoics studied argument and language because agents must distinguish sound impressions from deceptive ones. They studied physics because living according to nature requires an account of the whole to which humans belong. They developed cosmopolitan and role-based ethics because rational beings are social, not isolated fortresses. Stoic exercises train attention, desire, assent, and action so that freedom from destructive passion becomes readiness for responsible participation rather than escape from feeling or obligation.'
    ],['stoicism','ethics','logic'],['zeno','cleanthes','chrysippus','epictetus'],[]),
    section('founding','Zeno and the Painted Stoa',[
      'Zeno of Citium began teaching in Athens around the start of the third century BCE. The school took its name from the Stoa Poikile, the Painted Porch where he taught, rather than from a private estate or founder’s name. Zeno had encountered Cynic philosophy, and Stoicism preserves the Cynic claim that virtue rather than conventional success determines a good life. It also builds a much more elaborate system around that ethical independence, incorporating logic, natural philosophy, theology, and a positive account of social roles.',
      'Stoicism emerged alongside Epicureanism and skeptical developments in Plato’s Academy. These schools responded differently to a shared Hellenistic situation in which older civic forms existed within larger kingdoms and unstable power relations. Zeno’s school did not answer uncertainty by retreating from society. It argued that a person belongs to a rationally ordered cosmos and must learn to perform appropriate actions within family, city, and wider human community. The early school’s writings survive mainly through later reports, so reconstruction requires comparing sources that are often hostile, selective, or separated by centuries.'
    ],['stoicism','cynicism','ancient-greek'],['zeno','diogenes','epicurus'],[]),
    section('early-school','Cleanthes, Chrysippus, and the making of a system',[
      'Cleanthes succeeded Zeno and is remembered especially for the Hymn to Zeus, which presents the cosmos as ordered by divine rational law. His life became an example of persistence, but reducing him to moral character misses his role in developing the school’s theology and continuity. Chrysippus, the third head, wrote extensively across logic, physics, and ethics and defended Stoicism against objections. Ancient reports credit him so strongly with securing the school that its survival was said to depend on his achievement.',
      'Chrysippus’ work matters because Stoic practical claims depend on difficult arguments. If virtue alone is good, the school must explain why health is reasonably chosen without becoming morally good. If fate orders every event, it must explain responsibility without making deliberation pointless. If passions involve judgments, it must explain involuntary appearances and the possibility of correction. Chrysippus developed distinctions that allowed the school to answer such pressures. Later Stoicism changed in emphasis, and much early technical material was lost, but Roman ethical writing remains unintelligible when detached from this systematic foundation.'
    ],['stoicism','logic','metaphysics'],['cleanthes','chrysippus','zeno'],['Hymn to Zeus']),
    section('one-system','Logic, physics, and ethics belong together',[
      'Stoics divided philosophy into logic, physics, and ethics while insisting that the parts support one another. Logic included formal inference, rhetoric, grammar, epistemology, and the testing of impressions. Physics studied bodies, causes, elements, soul, divine reason, and the structure and cycles of the cosmos. Ethics asked how rational and social animals should live within that order. Ancient analogies compare philosophy to an organism, egg, or field whose parts cannot simply be discarded without changing the whole.',
      'The integration becomes visible in ordinary practice. An insulting remark produces an impression; logical and epistemic training helps the agent test what it means. Physical theory says the event occurs within an ordered causal world and that the speaker’s action belongs to the speaker’s character. Ethics asks what response accords with justice, self-command, and an appropriate social role. A modern reader may accept the ethical exercise while rejecting Stoic cosmology, but that is a selective reconstruction. Historical understanding requires seeing why the original exercise appeared rational within a material, providential, and causally connected universe.'
    ],['stoicism','logic','metaphysics','ethics'],['chrysippus','epictetus'],[]),
    section('nature-virtue','Living according to nature and virtue as the only good',[
      'Living according to nature does not mean obeying every impulse or imitating a romantic wilderness. For Stoics, human nature is rational and social, and the whole cosmos is ordered by logos, divine reason. A good life brings judgment and action into agreement with both dimensions. Virtue is knowledge expressed as excellent activity: wisdom, justice, courage, and moderation are not detachable possessions but coordinated ways of reasoning and acting. Because virtue completes the distinctively human capacity, it is sufficient for happiness even when circumstances are painful.',
      'This sufficiency claim is deliberately demanding. Illness, bereavement, poverty, and political defeat can make life difficult and appropriately call for action, but they cannot turn a just person into a bad one merely by occurring. Critics ancient and modern argue that severe suffering can undermine agency and that the doctrine understates material conditions. Stoics answer by separating what is genuinely admirable from what is fortunate. The point is not to call suffering good. It is to deny that fortune has final authority over whether a person acts with justice and practical reason.'
    ],['stoicism','virtue-ethics','ethics'],['zeno','epictetus','aristotle'],[]),
    section('indifferents','Preferred indifferents and appropriate selection',[
      'If virtue alone is good, Stoics still need to explain why a reasonable person seeks health, food, shelter, friendship, education, and political stability. They classify such things as indifferents with respect to moral goodness: possessing them does not make a vicious person good, and lacking them does not make a virtuous person bad. Among indifferents, some are preferred because they accord with nature, while others are dispreferred. This creates room for practical selection without turning success into the measure of character.',
      'The distinction is subtle and often abused. Calling health indifferent does not mean medical care is pointless, nor does calling wealth preferred authorize accumulation without limit. A Stoic should pursue preferred outcomes through appropriate action while accepting that their completion depends on causes beyond one agent. The reservation often expressed as “if nothing prevents” marks this structure. Action can be vigorous because its moral worth lies in intelligent and just use, not in a guarantee of victory. The doctrine therefore separates commitment from desperation, though it remains vulnerable when used to minimize another person’s deprivation.'
    ],['stoicism','ethics'],['chrysippus','epictetus','seneca'],[]),
    section('fate-responsibility','Fate, providence, and responsibility',[
      'Stoic physics describes a thoroughly causal cosmos permeated by active rational principle. Fate is not an external script imposed on nature; it is the network of causes through which events occur. Providence names the rational order of the whole, though particular events can appear destructive from a limited human viewpoint. Some early Stoics also described recurring cosmic conflagrations and renewals. This material and theological universe differs sharply from both Platonic separation and Epicurean atoms moving without providential design.',
      'Determinism creates an immediate problem for responsibility. Chrysippus reportedly answered with examples distinguishing initiating causes from the character through which a response unfolds. An external push begins a cylinder’s motion, but its shape explains how it rolls; an impression occurs, but the agent’s formed disposition matters to assent. Modern readers may find this insufficient, yet the strategy is clear: actions belong to the causal order and remain attributable to agents because their reasoning and character are genuine causes. Deliberation is not outside fate; it is one of the ways future action is caused.'
    ],['stoicism','metaphysics','ethics'],['chrysippus','cleanthes'],[]),
    section('emotion-assent','Impressions, assent, judgment, and emotion',[
      'Stoic psychology does not simply command the removal of emotion. It analyzes passions as excessive impulses connected with mistaken judgments about good and evil. Fear treats a future external event as an evil that threatens the good life; anger judges retaliation appropriate because an intolerable wrong has occurred; uncontrolled appetite treats an external object as necessary for happiness. Impressions can arise involuntarily, but assent gives them authority. Philosophical training intervenes between appearance and endorsement so that action becomes less captive to exaggeration.',
      'The ideal of apatheia means freedom from passions understood in this destructive sense, not numbness or inability to care. Stoics also recognize good feelings associated with correct judgment, including rational joy, caution, and wish. Attachment and grief remain difficult tests. Roman Stoics acknowledge the first movements of emotion and the pain of loss while insisting that love should not become a demand that mortal people never change or die. Critics question whether the analysis intellectualizes emotion too strongly. Its enduring insight is that feelings often contain claims about value that can be examined without condemning the person who feels them.'
    ],['stoicism','ethics','epistemology'],['chrysippus','seneca','epictetus'],['On Anger','Discourses']),
    section('social-ethics','Oikeiosis, cosmopolitanism, duty, and roles',[
      'Stoic ethics begins not with an isolated adult reasoner but with living beings oriented toward self-preservation and awareness of what belongs to them. The concept of oikeiosis describes appropriation, affiliation, or recognition of what is one’s own. In human development, rational understanding can extend concern through family, neighbors, fellow citizens, and ultimately humanity. Stoic cosmopolitanism follows from shared rational nature: people belong to one moral community even when laws and political status deny equal standing.',
      'Appropriate actions arise within concrete roles and relationships. A person acts as child, parent, sibling, friend, citizen, and participant in humanity, and must judge what fidelity to these relations requires. Hierocles’ image of concentric circles later expressed the work of drawing distant others closer in concern. Stoic practice therefore cannot be reduced to private resilience. Ancient Stoics did not consistently escape the hierarchies of their societies, and cosmopolitan language could coexist with empire and slavery. Even so, the tradition supplies resources for criticizing the idea that moral concern ends at a city’s border or a person’s rank.'
    ],['stoicism','political-philosophy','ethics'],['epictetus','marcus-aurelius','seneca'],['On Duties','Discourses']),
    section('roman-stoicism','Seneca, Epictetus, and Marcus Aurelius',[
      'Roman-period Stoicism survives in unusually personal and practical forms. Seneca writes letters, essays, and tragedies while entangled in wealth and imperial politics. His discussions of anger, grief, time, mercy, and moral progress expose the gap between doctrine and an imperfect practitioner. Epictetus teaches students to locate freedom in prohairesis, test impressions, and perform social roles without making outcomes conditions of integrity. Marcus Aurelius records private exercises addressed to himself while governing an empire.',
      'These writers do not replace early Stoic logic and physics, but they shift the surviving evidence toward ethical formation. Their genres matter. Seneca’s letters construct a relationship of mutual progress; Epictetus’ Discourses preserve confrontational teaching; the Meditations are notes of self-correction rather than public commandments. Reading them together reveals a tradition adapting to different positions of power. It also exposes tensions: a former enslaved teacher, a wealthy adviser, and an emperor can repeat shared principles while facing radically different responsibilities and temptations.'
    ],['stoicism','ethics','political-philosophy'],['seneca','epictetus','marcus-aurelius'],['Moral Letters','Discourses','Meditations']),
    section('rivals','Epicureans, skeptics, and Cynic inheritance',[
      'Stoicism inherits Cynic ethical independence and frank criticism of convention, but rejects a simple abandonment of institutions and develops a systematic physics and logic. Against Epicureanism, Stoics deny that pleasure is the good and reject a non-providential atomic cosmos. Both schools discipline desire and fear, yet Stoics emphasize virtue within social duty while Epicureans emphasize tranquility, friendship, and limits to ambition. Their disagreement concerns not lifestyle branding but the nature of value and the world in which choice occurs.',
      'Skeptical arguments challenge Stoic confidence that some impressions can securely grasp reality. Academic skeptics pressed the school to explain how a wise person could distinguish a cognitive impression from a convincing false appearance. Stoics defended criteria of knowledge and the possibility of expertise, while Pyrrhonists sought suspension of judgment where opposed arguments remained unsettled. These debates sharpened Stoic epistemology and show that tranquility was not the school’s only aim. Stoics valued truth and rational agreement with nature even when inquiry itself created difficulty.'
    ],['stoicism','epicureanism','skepticism','cynicism'],['zeno','epicurus','sextus-empiricus','diogenes'],[]),
    section('misunderstandings-reading','Misunderstandings, revival, and how to start reading',[
      'Stoicism has been revived as resilience training, leadership advice, therapeutic practice, and a philosophy of personal agency. These uses can be productive, but three distortions recur. Stoicism is not emotionlessness: it examines the judgments within destructive passions. It is not passivity: appropriate action and social duty remain required without guaranteed outcomes. It is not a productivity hack: virtue, justice, and cosmopolitan obligation cannot be replaced by efficiency or individual success. Modern practice becomes selective when it removes physics and providence, and should acknowledge that reconstruction openly.',
      'Begin with Epictetus’ Discourses before relying on the compact Enchiridion. Read selected letters of Seneca on anger, grief, time, and friendship, then approach Marcus Aurelius as private exercises shaped by Epictetus rather than as detached quotations. Use Cicero and other ancient reporters to encounter early Stoic arguments, since the founding texts are mostly lost. Throughout, ask how logic, physics, and ethics support one another. The central Stoic test is not whether a passage produces calm, but whether it clarifies judgment and enables just action when fortune offers neither comfort nor control.'
    ],['stoicism','ethics','logic'],['epictetus','seneca','marcus-aurelius','chrysippus'],['Discourses','Enchiridion','Moral Letters','Meditations'])
  ],
  epicureanism:[
    section('overview','A therapeutic system of nature, desire, and friendship',[
      'Epicureanism is a philosophical school organized around the claim that pleasure is the good and that the most reliable pleasure is freedom from bodily pain and mental disturbance. That claim belongs to a complete system. Atomist physics removes fear of divine intervention and death; epistemology explains how inquiry can trust experience without treating every opinion as true; ethics classifies desires and choices; friendship supplies security; and communal practice makes simple living sustainable. The parts work together as therapy directed against anxiety, superstition, rivalry, and unlimited wanting.',
      'The school’s name became a synonym for refined consumption, but historical Epicureanism is suspicious of dependence on luxury. It asks whether a pleasure leaves a person freer or creates a new need, whether a desire has a natural limit, and whether ambition exchanges peace for unstable approval. Epicureans do not promise permanent intensity or exemption from pain. They argue that understanding nature and limits can make happiness less vulnerable to fortune. This is why bread, water, conversation, memory, and confidence about mortality can matter more than the banquet used to caricature them.'
    ],['epicureanism','ethics','metaphysics'],['epicurus','lucretius'],[]),
    section('garden','Epicurus and the Garden',[
      'Epicurus founded the Garden in Athens around 306 BCE after teaching elsewhere in the Greek world. The school developed alongside Stoicism, Skepticism, Plato’s Academy, and Aristotle’s Lyceum, but established a distinctive social and intellectual environment. Ancient evidence indicates participation by women and enslaved people, though the surviving record cannot support a modern picture of complete equality. Members treated Epicurus’ teachings as a shared path to freedom from disturbance and maintained communities and correspondence beyond Athens.',
      'The Garden made friendship a philosophical institution rather than an optional comfort. Epicureans valued practical assistance, frank speech, recollection of teachings, and confidence that friends would remain present under difficulty. Withdrawal from public ambition was not withdrawal from all human connection. It was an attempt to build relationships less corrupted by competition for rank. The community also preserved a strong identity and loyalty to Epicurus, raising questions about authority within a school devoted to freedom from superstition. Its endurance shows that therapy required habits, teachers, and social trust, not isolated acceptance of a few arguments.'
    ],['epicureanism','ancient-greek'],['epicurus','lucretius'],['Vatican Sayings']),
    section('atomism','Atoms, void, and explanation without providence',[
      'Epicurean physics adapts Democritean atomism. Everything bodily consists of atoms and void; compounds form, change, and dissolve, while the basic constituents persist. The soul is a particularly fine bodily compound and does not survive the organism’s death. The gods, if understood as existing beings, do not create or administer the world. Natural phenomena arise through natural causes rather than messages of anger, reward, or punishment. These doctrines target fear by removing the supernatural interpretations through which uncertain events acquire terrifying personal meaning.',
      'The atomic swerve, especially known through Lucretius, describes a minimal deviation that prevents atomic motion from being only parallel fall and collision determined from eternity. Its exact role in Epicurean accounts of agency remains disputed. More broadly, the school permits multiple natural explanations of distant phenomena when evidence cannot decide among them. The therapeutic requirement is not false certainty but exclusion of mythic terror. This differs from Stoic providence and Aristotelian teleology: nature contains regular structures, but it is not organized as a rational plan aimed at human or cosmic purposes.'
    ],['epicureanism','metaphysics','philosophy-of-science'],['democritus','epicurus','lucretius'],['Letter to Herodotus','On the Nature of Things']),
    section('knowledge','Sensation, preconceptions, and feelings as criteria',[
      'Epicureans identify sensations, preconceptions, and feelings as criteria of truth. Sensation provides appearances generated through bodily interaction with the world. A sensation does not make the added judgment about its cause automatically true; error arises when opinion outruns confirmation. This allows Epicureans to defend perception against skepticism while explaining illusion. The distant object really appears a certain way from that position, but the observer must test whether the appearance warrants a conclusion about the object’s shape or size.',
      'Preconceptions are general recognitions built from repeated encounters and used when thinking and speaking about kinds of things. Feelings of pleasure and pain orient choice and avoidance. These criteria support inquiry because they provide contact points that argument cannot discard without undermining itself. Epicurean epistemology is therefore neither naive trust in every appearance nor suspension of judgment about everything. It supplies enough confidence to reason about imperceptible atoms from observable effects and enough caution to withhold claims where evidence permits several explanations.'
    ],['epicureanism','epistemology','skepticism'],['epicurus','sextus-empiricus'],['Letter to Herodotus','Principal Doctrines']),
    section('pleasure-desire','Pleasure, pain, tranquility, and the limits of desire',[
      'Epicurean ethics identifies pleasure with the goal of life, but distinguishes stable freedom from pain and disturbance from pleasures that vary or stimulate. A person whose hunger is satisfied already enjoys a complete bodily ease; richer food may vary the experience but cannot make the removal of hunger more complete. Mental tranquility depends on understanding what is necessary and what threatens future disturbance. Practical wisdom evaluates pleasures and pains across time, choosing painful efforts when they secure health or freedom and rejecting attractions that produce dependency.',
      'The classification of desires makes this evaluation teachable. Natural and necessary desires have recognizable limits connected to life, bodily ease, and happiness. Natural but unnecessary desires can be enjoyed without becoming conditions of well-being. Empty desires for unlimited wealth, power, fame, or immortality lack a natural point of completion and grow through comparison. Epicurean simplicity is not worship of deprivation. It is confidence that enough is attainable. This confidence reduces the leverage of rulers, markets, and social rivals who promise security only through permanent acquisition.'
    ],['epicureanism','ethics'],['epicurus'],['Letter to Menoeceus','Principal Doctrines']),
    section('friendship-justice','Friendship, community, and justice',[
      'Friendship occupies a striking place in a philosophy sometimes described as egoistic. Epicureans explain its value partly through security: friends help one another face illness, scarcity, and threat. Yet trust and affection become valued for themselves within the life they make possible. Friendship changes anticipation, replacing the isolated person’s fear of future danger with confidence in mutual aid. The school’s communities embodied this claim through shared practice, commemoration, correspondence, and instruction.',
      'Epicurean justice is commonly described as an agreement neither to harm nor be harmed. Justice is not a transcendent Form or command written into providential nature. It concerns arrangements that secure mutual advantage, and its concrete requirements can vary with circumstances. This conventional dimension does not mean any law is just. A rule that no longer serves mutual security loses the relevant character of justice even if authorities retain it. The account offers a naturalistic explanation of political obligation while also encouraging caution about public ambition, since power struggles often multiply fear rather than protect peaceful association.'
    ],['epicureanism','political-philosophy','ethics'],['epicurus'],['Principal Doctrines','Vatican Sayings']),
    section('gods-death','Gods, death, and ethics as the removal of fear',[
      'Epicurean theology separates divinity from providential government. Blessed and imperishable gods would not be angry, needy, or occupied with punishing human beings. Traditional stories that portray divine jealousy and intervention project human disturbance onto divine life. Interpreters dispute how literally Epicureans understood the gods, but the practical conclusion is consistent: unusual events should not be read as personal warnings from supernatural rulers. Natural explanation and a transformed conception of blessedness remove a major source of manipulation and anxiety.',
      'Death is nothing to us because experience requires sensation and the dead no longer sense. The argument addresses fear of being dead, not every pain associated with dying or bereavement. It also attacks the fantasy that happiness requires unlimited duration. When mortality is understood, the value of a life need not be measured by endless extension, and present choices no longer serve an impossible demand to defeat death. Epicurean therapy joins this argument to memory, friendship, and gratitude. Past pleasure can remain available in recollection even when the body suffers, as Epicurus’ reported final days were meant to demonstrate.'
    ],['epicureanism','philosophy-of-religion','ethics'],['epicurus','lucretius'],['Letter to Menoeceus','On the Nature of Things']),
    section('texts-practice','Ethics as therapy and the surviving textual practice',[
      'Epicureans compare philosophical argument to medicine. A doctrine should diagnose a disturbance, identify the false belief sustaining it, and support repeated practice until judgment changes. Compact formulations helped students remember the treatment when fear returned. The Letter to Menoeceus addresses gods, death, desire, pleasure, and wisdom in compressed form. The Principal Doctrines and Vatican Sayings preserve memorable claims about limits, friendship, justice, and security. These texts should be read as instruments within a community of practice, not as detached motivational quotations.',
      'The loss of most Epicurean writings makes the surviving tradition uneven. Diogenes Laertius preserves letters and doctrines; papyri from Herculaneum reveal later Epicurean discussion, especially associated with Philodemus; inscriptions such as that of Diogenes of Oenoanda show an attempt to make therapy publicly available. Epicurean practice included study of nature, examination of desire, frank criticism among friends, recollection of exemplary lives, and gratitude for available pleasure. The school sought reliable formation while warning against the ambitions and fears that often organize formal public life.'
    ],['epicureanism','ethics'],['epicurus','lucretius'],['Letter to Menoeceus','Principal Doctrines','Vatican Sayings']),
    section('lucretius','Lucretius and Roman Epicureanism',[
      'Lucretius’ De Rerum Natura is the fullest surviving presentation of Epicurean philosophy and one of its most consequential transformations. Written in Latin verse during the first century BCE, the poem explains atoms, void, sensation, mortality, cosmic formation, desire, civilization, and disease. Its poetic form is not an ornamental wrapper around scientific doctrine. Lucretius must make natural explanation vivid enough to compete with the fears and attractions sustained by myth, ambition, and erotic obsession.',
      'Roman Epicureanism included communities and thinkers beyond Lucretius, including Philodemus, whose Herculaneum texts discuss ethics, music, rhetoric, and frank speech. The tradition adapted a Greek school to Roman literary and political settings while maintaining suspicion of destructive ambition. Lucretius’ closing account of plague is especially challenging. Rather than end with effortless tranquility, the poem confronts readers with panic and social breakdown. The scene tests whether natural explanation can remain available when fear is collective and severe, showing that therapy is difficult practice rather than automatic consolation.'
    ],['epicureanism','ancient-greek'],['lucretius','epicurus'],['On the Nature of Things']),
    section('rivals','Stoicism, Platonism, Aristotle, and Skepticism',[
      'Epicureanism and Stoicism agree that philosophy should train desire and reduce servitude to fortune, but their systems diverge. Stoics affirm providential causal order, virtue as the only good, and substantial duties within social roles. Epicureans affirm non-providential atomism, pleasure as the good, friendship, and caution toward ambition. Epicurean tranquility is not a weaker version of Stoic courage; it follows from a different physics and theory of value. Each school accuses the other of misunderstanding what makes a life free.',
      'Epicureans reject Platonic Forms, an immortal soul, and the educational authority attached to transcendent standards. They reject Aristotelian teleology and the claim that flourishing is naturally completed through political participation. Against Skepticism, they defend criteria that make knowledge and natural explanation possible, although their willingness to accept multiple explanations where evidence is limited resembles disciplined caution. These disputes clarify the school’s ambition: it does not merely offer lifestyle advice but attempts to replace rival pictures of reality, knowledge, and human fulfillment.'
    ],['epicureanism','stoicism','platonism','aristotelianism','skepticism'],['epicurus','zeno','plato','aristotle','sextus-empiricus'],[]),
    section('hostility-revival','Hostility, atomist revival, and modern reception',[
      'Epicureanism faced ancient polemic and later Christian hostility because it denied providential government, the immortal soul, and punishment after death. Its name became associated with atheism and sensual excess even when critics knew its actual discipline. Some Epicurean communities and texts persisted, but much of the corpus disappeared. The early modern recovery of Lucretius contributed to renewed discussion of atomism, mortality, natural religion, and material explanation, though modern thinkers often transformed the doctrine rather than restoring the ancient school.',
      'Contemporary interest draws on Epicurean accounts of enough, friendship, anxiety, mortality, and freedom from consumer desire. These recoveries can correct the indulgence caricature but create another simplification if Epicureanism becomes minimalism without physics or private wellness without community. The tradition’s challenge is more demanding. It asks which institutions profit from unlimited fear and desire, whether natural explanations alter emotional life, and whether people can construct forms of friendship that make competitive status less necessary. Its political force often lies in withdrawing belief from the goods by which power secures obedience.'
    ],['epicureanism','philosophy-of-science','ethics'],['epicurus','lucretius'],['On the Nature of Things']),
    section('misunderstandings-reading','Misunderstandings and how to start reading',[
      'Three misunderstandings obscure Epicureanism. First, hedonism does not mean maximizing intense indulgence; it means organizing choice around stable pleasure and freedom from disturbance. Second, withdrawal from corrosive ambition does not mean selfish isolation; friendship is a central condition of security and happiness. Third, the Epicurean treatment of gods is not exhausted by simple denial. It attacks fear-producing providence and redefines blessed existence as free from anger and need. These corrections reveal a rigorous school rather than an ancient permission slip.',
      'Begin with Epicurus’ Letter to Menoeceus, then read the Principal Doctrines and Vatican Sayings as compact therapeutic prompts. Add the Letter to Herodotus to understand why physics is ethically necessary. Read substantial selections from Lucretius on atoms, fear of death, desire, and natural history, keeping poetry and argument together. Then compare the school with Stoic accounts of providence, virtue, and duty. A good reading asks of every doctrine: which fear does this remove, which desire does it limit, what evidence supports it, and what shared practices would make the resulting freedom durable?'
    ],['epicureanism','stoicism','ethics'],['epicurus','lucretius','zeno'],['Letter to Menoeceus','Principal Doctrines','Vatican Sayings','Letter to Herodotus','On the Nature of Things'])
  ]
};
